  <static seed="1449" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations25.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{y}{4y+12}-\frac{3}{y+3}}={4}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{-4\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{4\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{y}{4y+12}-\frac{3}{y+3}} \amp = {4} \\
  {\frac{y}{4\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right)}-\frac{3}{y+3}} \amp = {4} \\
  {\frac{y}{4\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right)}\cdot 4\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right)-\frac{3}{y+3}\cdot 4\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right)} \amp = {16\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right)} \\
  {y-12} \amp = {16y+48} \\
  {y-16y} \amp = {48-\left(-12\right)} \\
  {-15y} \amp = {60} \\
  \frac{{-15y}}{-15} \amp = \frac{{60}}{-15} \\
  y \amp = -4
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp 4y+12 = 0 \amp \;\amp  y+3=0 \\
   \amp 4y = -12 \amp \;\amp  y=-3 \\
   \amp \frac{4y}{4} = \frac{-12}{4} \\
   \amp y = -3 \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>-3</m> from the solution set. This value is not in the solution set we got, so the final solution is <m>y=-4</m>.</p>
</solution>
